            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adam Reyes\u2019s life has been a study in a single, refined passion. Raised in Marin County, his childhood was comfortable, colored by his paternal grandfather\u2019s stories of a youth spent in Spain\u2019s Rioja region. While his parents, a sensible accountant and a schoolteacher, encouraged a stable career, it was these inherited tales of vineyards and harvests that planted a seed. The name Reyes, a remnant of that Spanish heritage, felt like a quiet mandate.\n\nA degree in Hospitality Management from San Francisco State University seemed a practical path, but his true education began after graduation. A six-month backpacking trip through Europe became his crucible. Standing in a family-run cellar in France's Rh\u00f4ne Valley, a world away from California, Adam had his epiphany. The complex story of soil, climate, and human hands captured in a single glass was the only story he wanted to tell.\n\nReturning to San Francisco, he dove headfirst into the restaurant world, starting as a barback and absorbing everything he could. He worked relentlessly, earning his sommelier certifications while developing a palate and a warm, unpretentious rapport with guests. His big break came three years ago when he was hired as Head Sommelier at a celebrated Michelin-starred restaurant in Hayes Valley.\n\nNow, Adam\u2019s life revolves around the rhythm of the restaurant. His 0.8-mile walk from his apartment to work is a daily ritual, a brief moment of quiet before the evening\u2019s performance. His days are a blur of inventory management, staff training, and meetings with vintners, culminating in the nightly service where he guides diners through his meticulously curated wine list. His social life is intertwined with his profession; late-night drinks with fellow industry workers are more common than weekend parties. A serious relationship ended amicably last year, a casualty of conflicting schedules, and he has since poured his energy back into his craft.\n\nAdam loves his corner of San Francisco\u2014the creative energy of Hayes Valley, the proximity to world-class food, the discerning clientele. His dream is to one day open his own establishment: a small, intimate wine bar in a neighborhood like his own, a place built not on trends, but on the timeless stories he first fell in love with, one bottle at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was fourteen, sitting with his grandfather on the porch in Marin, a glass of deep red Tempranillo swirling in the old man's hand. The air smelled of dust and dried cherries as his grandfather spoke not of wine, but of the sun-baked Spanish soil. In that moment, watching the light catch the ruby liquid, Adam felt a quiet pull, a sense of belonging to a story much older than himself. The name Reyes suddenly felt less like a last name and more like a map.\n\n2.\nHe was twenty-two, standing in a cold, damp cellar in the Rh\u00f4ne Valley. The vigneron, a man with earth permanently etched into his hands, poured him a Syrah directly from the barrel. As the raw, peppery wine hit his tongue, everything crystallized. It wasn't just a beverage; it was a biography of a place, a climate, and a life\u2019s work. He knew then, with absolute certainty, that his purpose was to translate these stories, to share that profound connection captured in a glass.\n\n3.\nThe first night after his promotion three years ago, he stayed late. He remembers the specific weight of the cellar key in his hand as he unlocked the door. Standing alone amidst the silent, sleeping bottles, he wasn't just an employee anymore; he was the custodian. The immense weight of responsibility felt strangely comforting, a quiet, profound validation for every grueling shift and sacrificed weekend. He had finally earned the right to shape the story the restaurant told each night.\n\n4.\nHe recalls the bottle of Sancerre they shared on their couch last year, the same one they\u2019d once celebrated with. This time, its bright acidity tasted sharp, almost clinical. There were no harsh words, just a shared, quiet understanding that their futures were on different timetables. The silence between sips confirmed everything. It was a melancholy acceptance\u2014the moment he understood the true, personal cost of his singular passion\u2014and he poured what was left of his energy back into his craft.\n\n5.\nA few months ago, a quiet older couple celebrated an anniversary. After listening to them, Adam chose a lesser-known Italian red, a wine with a story of resilience. He watched as the woman took a sip, her eyes closing briefly before a soft, genuine smile spread across her face. Her husband simply nodded at Adam, a look of profound gratitude. That single, non-verbal exchange of shared joy was everything\u2014the entire reason for the long hours, the very soul of his future wine bar."
